2026-07-21T17:00:00Z,"Everyone does the math on rent and stops there, and that's how people end up broke by the 15th of the month. Before you sign anything, add up the full picture: deposit, first and sometimes last month's rent, application fees, pet fees if you have a dog or cat, renters insurance, and utilities that aren't included. A $1,200/month apartment can easily cost you $3,000+ just to walk through the door. And don't forget the ongoing stuff — electric, water, internet, parking. A good rule most people use is keeping rent under 30% of your take-home pay, but if you're in a pricier city that's not always realistic, so just be honest with yourself about what you can actually afford without stress every month. Ask the landlord upfront exactly what's included so there are no surprises on your first bill. It's a lot easier to walk away from a place before you sign than to break a lease six months in because the numbers didn't work.
#RentingTips #ApartmentHunting #BudgetingForRent #FirstApartment #RenterLife",1.jpg,publish,true,0
